import{_ as t,o,c as r,a,d as e,e as n,b as s}from"./app-de7a4551.js";const i={},h=e("h1",{id:"why-your-life-needs-novelty-no-matter-your-age-2",tabindex:"-1"},[e("a",{class:"header-anchor",href:"#why-your-life-needs-novelty-no-matter-your-age-2","aria-hidden":"true"},"#"),n(" Why Your Life Needs Novelty, No Matter Your Age (2)")],-1),d=s('<p>So after about 30 seconds, I decide to <code>mimic</code>.<br> And so I lay in this fresh bed of snow in Montana, I move my arms and my legs.<br> And then it <em>dawns on me</em>.<br> I&#39;m making a snow angel for the first time. And of course, I&#39;ve seen other people do it and I&#39;ve seen it on television before.<br> But it was the first time I did it.<br> You see, I&#39;ve <code>coined</code> the term powerful first experiences or PFEs as doing something you never thought you would do for the first time, in a place that you never thought you would be in for the first time.<br> The main reason why I was in Montana in the first place was to give a talk about powerful first experiences,<br> so it was <em>only right</em> that I would then have powerful first experiences in Montana.<br> Powerful first experiences are <em>life-altering</em> moments and experiences that change the way that we see ourselves and changes the way we see the world.<br> And it can be as expansive as <code>skydiving</code> out of a plane in France or as small as visiting a lake to <code>meditate</code> for the first time.<br> What matters is your imagination, your courage and your curiosity.</p><details class="custom-container details"><summary>translation</summary><p><strong>sentence:</strong><br> 大约 30 秒后，我打算模仿她。<br> 我躺在了蒙大拿刚下的雪地上，动起了我的手臂和腿，<br> 我恍然大悟，<br> 这是我第一次做雪天使。<br> 当然，我看过别人这么做，之前也在电视上看到过。<br> 但这是我第一次这么做。<br> 我自创了&quot;震撼的第一次&quot;或者 PFE 这个词，意思是做那些你从未想过要做的事，在你从未想过会做这件事的地方。<br> 我到蒙大拿的主要原因本来就是要做一场关于&quot;震撼的第一次&quot;的演讲，<br> 所以我在蒙大拿有了一场&quot;震撼的第一次&quot;也是理所因当。<br> 震撼的第一次是改变人生的瞬间和经历，改变了我们看待自己的方式，改变了我们看待世界的方式。<br> 可以像在法国极限跳伞这么大型的经历，也可以像第一次前往一个湖泊冥想这么微不足道。<br> 重要的是你的想象力、勇气和好奇心。</p></details><p>In the book &quot;Power of Moments&quot; by Chip and Dan Heath, the authors reference what psychologists call the <code>reminiscence</code> bump,<br> a phenomenon where <em>older <code>individuals</code></em> are asked to think about their experiences, where they <em>tend to</em> <code>disproportionately</code> talk about the experiences that happened roughly between the ages of 15 to 30.<br> Some researchers say this is a time in our lives when we experience the most novelty.<br> And there&#39;s a few theories why.<br> One, when you enter and <em>pass through</em> your 30s, life can <em>seem like</em> it speeds up because we develop the habits of doing the same things over and over.<br> Another reason is that there are just some experiences in our lives that are <em>set to</em> happen <code>within</code> that <em>time frame</em>.<br> So think about it. By 15, you might be in high school.<br> By 18, you may be in college.<br> After college, you get a job, you may buy the big home, you may get married, you may have a kid.</p><details class="custom-container details"><summary>translation</summary><p><strong>sentence:</strong><br> 在希思兄弟（Chip and Dan Heath）的书《时刻的力量》（Power of Moments）中，作者引用了心理学家所称的&quot;记忆隆起&quot;，<br> 即在要求老年人回忆以往经历时，他们会滔滔不绝地谈论他们 15 至 30 岁左右的经历。<br> 有些研究者称，这段时间是我们人生中经历最多新奇事物的时候。<br> 有许多理论可以解释其中原因。<br> 一个原因是，当你走进 30 岁，度过了三十多岁的人生，就会感觉人生加速了，因为我们形成了一遍又一遍地做同一件事的习惯。<br> 另一个原因是人生中就是有一些事只会在那段时间里发生。<br> 想想看。到了 15 岁，你在读高中。<br> 到了 18 岁，你在读大学。<br> 读完了大学，你找了份工作，买座大房子，结婚，生个娃。</p></details>',4);function m(c,u){return o(),r("div",null,[h,a(" 为什么你的生活需要新奇，无论你的年龄（2）  "),d])}const b=t(i,[["render",m],["__file","23-needs-novelty-2.html.vue"]]);export{b as default};
